title: For Sale:  Vintage Browning SA-22 grade II
postcontent: This is a Browning SA-22. Not just any SA-22, this one is quite special. You will never find another one like this. 1970’s UNFIRED, NIB, never even assembled outside of the factory. This piece even includes the original outer shipping box!The SA-22 is the first majorly successful takedown semi automatic .22 that has ever been produced. It is such a successful design that to this day it is still being produced, a claim that not many other guns can share. Starting in 1974, the production of all Browning SA-22’s were moved from Belgium to Japan. Specifically Miroku, Japan. Both Browning and Winchester firearms produced in Miroku are renowned for their incredible quality with fit, finish, accuracy, workmanship, and materials used.This Browning is a Grade II and is absolutely mint, new in the box. The gun has never even been put together after it was shipped. Since the box has been opened, I have to say it is 99% for the wood and 99% for the metal. The components were only removed for the pictures and returned right to their box after being wiped down with a gun cloth to ensure there would be no oils/acids from finger prints or any other potential impurity left behind.The gun comes with its outer shipping box which is of course a perfect fit for the inner box. The outer box states that this rifle was shipped to a gun shop in Frankfort, Michigan, on September 28th, 1979. What is particularly odd with this is the serial number. According to the Browning website, it appears this rifle was produced in 1980 due to the PM after the serial number. There is a intriguing overlap on dates with this one which makes it all the more interesting.With any Browning firearm, this has fantastic wood and the high luster sheen. I did my best to take pictures, but we all know how bright pictures of the wood can get. The checkering is the classic pointed variety, and appears hand done. It is deep and sharp as new checkering should be. The grain pattern on this stock is simply stunning. Wood to metal fit is outstanding with no cracks, chips, or scrapes. Again, it was not ever even assembled. The butt plate is un messed with, and the magazine tube was not removed.The bluing is flawless as can be expected, and is the typical Browning high luster polish. The barrel is 19.25”. Unlike many of these, the takedown mechanism and threading is perfect as you can see.The receiver is in the white, and has intricate engraving on both the left(ground hogs and scroll) and right side(squirrels and scroll), in addition to the top of the receiver(a duck and scroll) and on the trigger guard itself(floral). There are no signs of bolt wear aside from the factory test fire, the bolt face is as a new gun should be. The trigger is gold. For sights this rifle has the typical folding rear sight and a post front sight.Overall, this is an amazing time capsule that literally cannot be improved upon. You don’t often run into NIB examples of the SA22 in any grade. Finding a grade II with the original outer shipping box is next to impossible. You can track where and when it went. This would make an excellent investment, or an heirloom piece to be proud of for generations to come. Take advantage of this while you can, you are not going to find another one.

U.S. Civil War Nilitary Frank Wesson Kittridge & Co 44 two trigger    650  $$     shoots 44 RF or CF  for CF it uses .44 russian ammo
Here is an original Wesson single-shot breechloading carbine in good condition. This .44 caliber, ‘two-trigger’ rimfire, Wesson military carbine is one of some 4,500 carbines produced at Worcester, Mass.   The two-line maker address found on to stampings read “F. WESSON’S PATENT / OCT. 25, 1859 / B. KITTREDGE & CO. / CINCINNATI. O.”   Records indicate that 1,366 Wesson ‘Kittredge-marked’ carbines were supplied to state units from Kentucky. Bore is good with strong five-groove rifling and pinprick rust overall. Should clean up to semi-bright.  A tip-up style action utilized with the froward trigger acting as the release for the barrel. When loading, the center-mounted hammer is brought to half cock freeing the barrel and lets the breech swing up on the forward pivot screw.
This Wesson ‘Kittredge” rimfire military carbine is a seldom-seen Civil War specimen certain to enhance any carbine collection.
